What we are trying to solve, in plain business language

We are solving 6 major business problems.

Problem 1: Cart abandonment

This is one of the biggest problems in e-commerce.

A customer:

* views a product
* adds it to cart
* maybe even starts checkout
* but does not complete the purchase

This means the company spent money attracting the customer, but did not get revenue.

Business impact

* lost sales
* wasted ad spend
* poor customer experience
* low conversion rate

What the business wants to know

* which products are most abandoned
* which categories have high abandonment
* whether certain countries abandon more
* whether certain traffic sources bring low-intent users
* whether mobile users abandon more than desktop users

Our project solves this by

combining clickstream and order data to identify:

* add_to_cart but no purchase
* checkout started but no completed order
* abandonment by product, category, country, source

⸻

Problem 2: High traffic but low conversion products

Some products get many views, but very few purchases.

That is dangerous because the product may look popular, but it is not making money.

Possible reasons

* bad price
* poor product description
* wrong target audience
* poor reviews
* out-of-stock issue
* shipping concern
* misleading ad traffic

Business impact

* marketing money wasted
* inventory decisions become wrong
* product ranking becomes misleading

What business wants

* top viewed products with low conversion
* category-level conversion rate
* compare views vs carts vs purchases

Our project solves this by

tracking the product funnel:

* product_view
* add_to_cart
* checkout_start
* purchase

and building product conversion KPIs.

⸻

Problem 3: No full customer journey visibility

The company often knows only the final order.

But business teams also want to know:

* where the customer came from
* what they viewed
* how long they browsed
* whether they abandoned first and bought later
* whether they are repeat customers
* whether they came from ads, search, direct traffic, or social media

Business impact

Without this:

* marketing attribution is weak
* retargeting is poor
* loyalty programs are less effective
* repeat customer strategy is incomplete

Our project solves this by

building a Customer 360 view that combines:

* customer activity
* session behavior
* purchases
* country/region
* source/channel
* repeat spending signals

⸻

Problem 4: Revenue reporting is fragmented

If the company sells globally, reporting becomes messy.

Example:

* US orders in USD
* Europe orders in EUR
* India orders in INR

If revenue is not converted into one common currency, business leaders cannot compare markets correctly.

Business impact

* wrong country performance analysis
* wrong board-level reporting
* hard to compare category performance globally

What business wants

* standardized revenue in one currency
* daily revenue by country
* revenue by category
* revenue by payment type
* average order value

Our project solves this by

using FX rate API data to convert all revenue into a reporting currency like USD.

⸻

Problem 5: Poor regional or shipping zone performance is hidden

Sometimes low sales are not because the product is bad.

Maybe:

* delivery is slower in that region
* shipping cost is high
* users from certain regions face friction
* time zone / operational issues affect purchase timing

Business impact

Business may blame product or campaign when the real problem is regional operations.

What business wants

* compare performance by country/region/shipping zone
* understand where drop-offs are happening
* identify low-performing geographies

Our project solves this by

enriching customer and order data with shipping zone / country metadata.

⸻

Problem 6: Marketing traffic quality is unclear

A campaign may drive lots of visitors.

But are those visitors buying?

Maybe one source brings:

* lots of clicks
* lots of product views
* almost no purchases

Another source may bring:

* fewer visitors
* but much higher conversion

Business impact

* ad budgets may be wasted
* campaign ROI may be misunderstood
* poor channels continue to receive spend

What business wants

* revenue by traffic source
* conversion by source
* abandonment by source
* campaign quality insights

Our project solves this by

linking clickstream traffic_source with purchase outcomes.

